@Zuluknob philosophically, yes. Technically, not as I understand brushless motors. 
The rotor doesn't have permanent magnets, but, I guess, inducted magnets. But if you used a controller to rotate some electromagnet's fields, it would be much like a brushless motor. 
You could physically rotate both outside edges and still use permanent magnets. Perhaps for more applied power and almost certainly greater top speed.
